WEBVTT

00:00.962 --> 00:04.125
Friends, welcome to Word on Fire Catholic Ministries.

00:04.686 --> 00:18.380
Word on Fire is an apostolate dedicated to the mission of evangelization, using media both old and new to share the faith on every continent and to facilitate an encounter with Christ and His Church.

00:19.121 --> 00:26.649
The efforts of Word on Fire engage the culture and bring the transformative power of God's Word where it is most needed.

00:26.709 --> 00:27.890
Today,

00:27.970 --> 00:35.982
We invite you to join Bishop Robert Barron as he preaches the gospel and shares the warmth and light of Christ with each one of us.

00:40.529 --> 00:41.571
Peace be with you, friends.

00:41.591 --> 00:47.079
We come to this 33rd Sunday of the year, which means next Sunday is the final Sunday of the year.

00:47.520 --> 00:54.130
So at this end of the year time, the church always gives us apocalyptic readings.

00:54.530 --> 00:58.456
Our gospel is from what's called the little apocalypse in the gospel of Luke.

00:58.957 --> 01:04.144
Now, as I've told you many times before, apocalypsis in Greek does not mean end of the world.

01:04.385 --> 01:10.454
What it means is unveiling, taking away the calypso, the veil.

01:10.995 --> 01:18.586
And that's why when apocalypsis is rendered in Latin, we get revvelatio, revelation, taking the vellum, taking the veil away.

01:19.287 --> 01:23.954
So they're all about, I put it this way, something old,

01:24.354 --> 01:32.047
being shaken and set aside, and then something new being unveiled.

01:32.167 --> 01:34.972
That's apocalyptic literature.

01:35.733 --> 01:46.572
Well, this little apocalypse in Luke, I think it's really interesting because it's showing you, I think, three shakings and then three unvailings.

01:47.914 --> 01:50.418
It's the showing forth of a new world.

01:51.042 --> 01:57.050
But that has to be preceded by a sort of shaking or setting aside of the old world.

01:57.431 --> 01:58.392
Now, what am I talking about?

01:59.414 --> 02:02.498
I'm talking about the resurrection of Jesus from the dead.

02:04.240 --> 02:05.422
That's the good news.

02:06.183 --> 02:07.344
That's the gospel.

02:08.246 --> 02:20.082
In their minds and hearts and on their lips was this message of Jesus risen from the dead, which they took to mean, listen now, that the old world

02:20.706 --> 02:29.335
with all of its priorities has been shaken, questioned, it's been marginalized, it's been relativized.

02:30.616 --> 02:33.539
And now a new world is revealed.

02:34.400 --> 02:36.942
Think of the tearing of the veil in the temple.

02:37.002 --> 02:41.247
We hear at the death of Jesus, the veil is torn from top to bottom.

02:43.149 --> 02:45.531
Access to the holy of holies, yes, it means that.

02:45.551 --> 02:48.434
But I think also it's the showing forth

02:49.218 --> 02:51.481
of something altogether new.

02:51.501 --> 03:02.418
You think for a second about that cross of Jesus, how all the powers of the world, all our certainties and finalities have gathered there.

03:03.059 --> 03:14.576
And you say, yeah, in the death of this poor man, the facts of life, the facts of the world, political, natural, religious, they're all there on display.

03:15.317 --> 03:18.482
And see the Christian gospel everybody says, no,

03:18.562 --> 03:25.491
All of those things that you consider absolute and final, they've been shaken by the resurrection of Jesus from the dead.

03:26.533 --> 03:32.741
And a new world has been unveiled to us, a new way of being.

03:33.081 --> 03:37.928
Okay, so with that principle in mind, let me try to show you in the text how this happened.

03:39.009 --> 03:45.618
So while people were speaking about how the temple was adorned with costly stones and votive offerings,

03:46.274 --> 03:49.399
So they're good, called them religious tourists here.

03:49.439 --> 03:52.623
They're Jesus disciples from the North, from Galilee.

03:52.643 --> 03:55.127
They're in a way, kind of country bumpkin types.

03:55.187 --> 04:04.721
And they've come to the capital, they've come to the temple, which especially in its Herodian renovation was like one of the wonders of the ancient world.

04:05.542 --> 04:10.009
And these simple fishermen from Galilee hadn't seen anything like that.

04:10.730 --> 04:13.714
And so of course they're amazed.

04:13.858 --> 04:20.128
a devout Catholic standing in front of St. Peter's Basilica and Rome, and you're admiring its architecture and art.

04:20.849 --> 04:22.111
That's where they are.

04:22.972 --> 04:23.913
And what does Jesus say?

04:24.875 --> 04:27.278
As usual, it's something a little bit unnerving.

04:28.320 --> 04:38.415
He said, all that you see here, the days will come when there will be not one stone left upon another, but every stone will be thrown down.

04:39.797 --> 04:40.178
Man.

04:40.642 --> 04:42.084
And shocking.

04:42.704 --> 04:45.047
Again, go back to a Catholic in front of St. Peter's.

04:45.688 --> 04:50.974
Let's say I was there with some friends and they're, oh, St. Peter's, how beautiful, how amazing.

04:51.154 --> 04:52.315
Look at the architecture.

04:52.896 --> 04:56.420
And I would say days are coming when they had a whole thing is gonna be torn down.

04:57.240 --> 05:03.728
And that'd give you a slight sense of what it was like to hear this sort of language.

05:03.748 --> 05:04.509
How do we interpret it?

05:05.670 --> 05:09.394
Well, I told you last week about Jesus cleansing of the temple.

05:09.538 --> 05:13.763
and announcing a prophetic denunciation upon the temple.

05:13.783 --> 05:17.407
What did they know in light of the resurrection of Jesus from the dead?

05:18.568 --> 05:24.975
They knew that everything they had taken to be religiously absolute has now been shaken.

05:25.035 --> 05:35.026
Think of all the customs, practices, everything that Jews of Jesus' time would have known, that their whole religious structure

05:35.266 --> 05:40.011
The entire religious institution beautifully summarized, summed up in the temple.

05:41.653 --> 05:44.677
Jesus says that days come on this, all going to be thrown down.

05:45.458 --> 05:45.698
Why?

05:45.758 --> 05:46.359
Why?

05:46.399 --> 06:03.058
Because the resurrection of Jesus from the dead is the stunning revelation, the stunning unveiling of the fullness of God's love and presence, of what

06:03.362 --> 06:05.085
Religion really ought to be.

06:07.408 --> 06:09.832
Religion, as they knew it, is shaken.

06:10.934 --> 06:12.096
But now he goes on.

06:12.496 --> 06:13.718
There's a second shaking.

06:14.960 --> 06:19.588
They ask, what are the signs when this great revelation is going to happen?

06:20.469 --> 06:27.019
He says, when you hear of wars and insurrections, don't be terrified for such things happen first.

06:27.921 --> 06:31.186
Nation will rise against nation, kingdom against kingdom.

06:31.906 --> 06:32.968
What was he talking about here?

06:33.008 --> 06:36.353
Well, something that's of perennial interest to human beings.

06:37.074 --> 06:46.188
From the beginning of history to today, we tend to be fascinated by politics, by the play of nation against nation.

06:46.209 --> 06:59.890
I pick up the paper every day and I look at, well, what's going on with the war here and this difficulty and the Middle East and as I record these words, Russia and Ukraine and the world of,

07:00.770 --> 07:07.177
political struggle, nation against nation warfare, who's winning, who's losing, who's up, who's down in the political order.

07:08.138 --> 07:11.662
We're fascinated by it as they were, as they were.

07:12.703 --> 07:21.032
Rome, and in relation to Judaism and the Roman Empire, and is it expanding and who's threatening it?

07:21.552 --> 07:23.434
And who's the Caesar now?

07:23.855 --> 07:25.577
And who's jockeying for position?

07:25.657 --> 07:28.560
And yeah, politics, we love politics.

07:28.600 --> 07:30.482
We're captivated by it.

07:31.458 --> 07:35.823
We tend to think it's one of the most basic and fundamental realities we cope with, right?

07:39.247 --> 07:46.234
All of that is shaken by the resurrection of Jesus from the dead.

07:47.656 --> 07:49.838
See, what did they know in light of the resurrection?

07:50.579 --> 08:00.530
Well, look, Caesar, he was the most powerful figure in the world, Caesar, through his local representative, Pontius Pilate, nailed Jesus to a cross.

08:01.122 --> 08:04.886
That's the full expression of Roman power.

08:05.546 --> 08:08.369
You want to see the Roman political reality on display?

08:08.449 --> 08:09.130
There it is.

08:12.433 --> 08:14.715
But God raised him.

08:15.236 --> 08:19.220
And that's one of the most primitive, we call it, karygmatic.

08:19.240 --> 08:22.703
It means the declaration of the fundamental gospel.

08:23.424 --> 08:29.970
One of the most fundamental karygmatic proclamations is, you killed him, God raised him.

08:30.658 --> 08:32.220
Well, you see what that means, everybody.

08:32.381 --> 08:34.864
It means Caesar is not the Lord anymore.

08:34.965 --> 08:39.051
It means Caesar and his great empire are not what finally matters.

08:39.792 --> 08:44.359
Whether he's rising or falling, who's coming, who's going, none of that finally matters.

08:45.120 --> 08:52.492
And that's why the first Christians went out with this impossible boldness saying, Jesus, carry us.

08:52.972 --> 08:54.034
Jesus is Lord.

08:54.594 --> 08:57.598
Jesus is Lord, not Caesar, not the nations.

08:58.179 --> 08:59.681
Nations rise against each other.

08:59.721 --> 09:01.183
Okay, they come and they go.

09:01.223 --> 09:07.171
What matters is Jesus risen from the dead.

09:07.631 --> 09:09.294
He shakes the religion they knew.

09:09.334 --> 09:17.184
He shakes the politics that they knew and reveals Revolazzio something new.

09:17.224 --> 09:23.873
Now the third shaking, it also has to do with something that we consider pretty ultimate.

09:23.953 --> 09:24.434
Now listen,

09:25.858 --> 09:33.586
There will be powerful earthquakes, famines and plagues from place to place and awesome sights and mighty signs will come from the sky."

09:34.807 --> 09:35.588
What's he talking about here?

09:35.648 --> 09:37.370
Nature.

09:38.531 --> 09:43.196
You know, especially for ancient people, true of us, especially now in our very materialistic time.

09:43.817 --> 09:52.626
But for the ancient people's nature, earth, air, sky, you know, the oceans, the mountains,

09:53.026 --> 09:54.088
Nature was it.

09:54.208 --> 09:57.233
Nature was the great context for reality.

09:58.315 --> 10:09.095
Even the gods, you look at the Greeks and Romans, the gods were very high sophisticated beings, but they existed within the context of nature.

10:09.115 --> 10:13.322
They were seen as literally living on Mount Olympus, for example.

10:13.342 --> 10:15.506
Nature, that's an ultimate reality.

10:18.146 --> 10:27.346
Again, we in our materialistic age, we've kind of reverted to that pagan view, but that's all there is, just the natural givenness of things.

10:28.689 --> 10:32.076
Now, what's one of the most basic truths we know about nature?

10:34.281 --> 10:36.947
Things die, right?

10:36.967 --> 10:38.450
Living things die.

10:39.202 --> 10:47.695
They come into being as living things out of the earth and through the reproductive systems of animals and so on, plants from seed, etc.

10:48.115 --> 10:55.687
Living things emerge and every living thing that's ever been that we know about dies.

10:56.768 --> 10:59.092
It's a basic truth of nature.

11:02.897 --> 11:08.626
Yeah, I know, but then there was the resurrection of Jesus from the dead.

11:08.770 --> 11:10.492
You catch it.

11:10.573 --> 11:12.215
You sense it in the Gospels.

11:15.079 --> 11:17.562
Jesus, who died, there's no question about it.

11:18.063 --> 11:19.765
Romans knew how to put people to death.

11:21.428 --> 11:22.089
They saw him.

11:22.349 --> 11:23.511
He died on the cross.

11:23.551 --> 11:26.355
He's buried days in the tomb.

11:26.415 --> 11:30.981
And then they see him alive.

11:32.383 --> 11:37.330
We who ate and drank with him after his resurrection from the dead.

11:37.442 --> 11:45.371
and they all went to their deaths as martyrs, referencing this truth.

11:47.314 --> 11:56.064
Well, if Jesus who died on the cross is through the power of God raised from the dead, that means nature isn't what we thought it was.

11:56.945 --> 12:01.951
It means the things we thought were absolute and unchanging aren't absolute and unchanging.

12:02.812 --> 12:04.754
Earthquakes, tell me about it because

12:05.250 --> 12:09.275
Something is being shaken about nature.

12:09.375 --> 12:16.183
Nature itself is giving way to something new.

12:17.685 --> 12:23.452
Something has been shaken and now unveiled to us.

12:25.154 --> 12:29.119
What they thought of as ultimate in matters of religion, that gives way.

12:30.701 --> 12:34.866
What they thought was ultimate in matters of politics at the matter anymore.

12:35.778 --> 12:41.025
Even what they thought was ultimate in nature is no longer the case.

12:42.347 --> 12:45.411
See, everybody, that's the radicality of the resurrection.

12:46.773 --> 12:52.660
The folly of turning Jesus into a, you know, finally remembered moral teacher from long ago.

12:52.680 --> 12:55.885
I mean, that's a complete betrayal of the gospel.

12:56.345 --> 12:57.266
And that's all he is.

12:57.407 --> 12:58.047
Who cares?

12:58.528 --> 12:59.209
Who cares?

12:59.790 --> 13:02.994
But the gospel is the good news that you won Gellion.

13:03.842 --> 13:20.728
is that something so fresh and new and unexpected and strange has happened, that the whole world that we knew is marginalized, is relativized, and something new has emerged.

13:22.351 --> 13:24.154
So what do we do?

13:25.175 --> 13:32.146
Well, we get about the business of ordering our lives, not according to the old religious forms,

13:32.354 --> 13:38.384
not according to old political realities, not even according to what we assume is the case about nature.

13:39.686 --> 13:48.079
But we get about the business of ordering our lives in accord with Christ Jesus, risen from the dead.

13:48.140 --> 13:50.403
Weird?

13:50.864 --> 13:57.074
Well, yeah, I mean, look, before I've done it, look what I'm wearing here, this cross with jewels on it.

13:57.250 --> 14:02.557
I mean, all of the poetry and weirdness of Christianity is fully on display here.

14:03.158 --> 14:05.902
Talk about, you know, political reality.

14:06.323 --> 14:09.187
Talk about the reality of what we assume is true of nature.

14:11.009 --> 14:12.331
Talk about the old religion.

14:12.371 --> 14:17.058
It's all shaken by this fact.

14:18.540 --> 14:25.650
And therefore, something in this cross and resurrection of Jesus is unveiled to us.

14:25.954 --> 14:27.216
Apocalypsis.

14:27.417 --> 14:28.499
Apocalypsis.

14:29.521 --> 14:30.763
A new world is emerged.

14:32.046 --> 14:32.687
And God bless you.

14:37.416 --> 14:41.003
Thank you for listening to this week's homily from Bishop Robert Barron.

14:41.404 --> 14:46.514
For more resources from Bishop Barron, please visit wordonfire.org.

